solution:
First, notice $2x - xy = x(2 - y)$. So this problem reduces to finding the values of $x$ and $y$.

Add the two equations together to find $x$: \begin{align*}
2x &= 20, \\
x &= 10.
\end{align*}
Subtract the two equations to find $y$: \begin{align*}
2y &= 4, \\
y &= 2.
\end{align*}
Since $y = 2$ and $x = 10$, $x(2 - y) = 10(2 - 2) = \boxed{0}$.

Applying the order of operations gives \begin{align*}
3\cdot 3 +3(3+3) - 3^3 &= 3\cdot 3 +3(6) - 3^3\\
&= 3\cdot 3 + 3(6) - 27\\
&= 9 + 18 - 27 = \boxed{0}.
\end{align*}

Simplify according to the order of operations. \begin{align*}
3!(2^3+\sqrt{9})\div 2 &= 6(8+3)\div 2 \\
&=6(11)\div 2 \\
&=66\div 2\\
&=\boxed{33}.
\end{align*}

The easiest solution is geometric. Recall that $|z|$ can be interpreted as the distance of $z$ from the origin in the complex plane; the given information tells us that $z$ lies on a circle of radius 5 and $w$ lies on a circle of radius 2. Drawing these circles in the complex plane, we see that $z$ and $w$ are closest together when they lie on a common radius, with $w$ in the same quadrant as $z$. This gives the minimum value of $|z-w|$ as $5 - 2 = \boxed{3}$. (This is a special case of the triangle inequality for complex numbers.)

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair Z, W;

Z = 2*dir(34);
W = 5*dir(78);

draw(Circle((0,0),2),red);
draw(Circle((0,0),5),blue);
draw(Z--W);

dot("$z$", Z, SW);
dot("$w$", W, N);
[/asy]

Let $P$ be the point on the unit circle that is $210^\circ$ counterclockwise from $(1,0)$, and let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $P$ to the $x$-axis, as shown below.

[asy]
pair A,C,P,O,D;
draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));
draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));
A = (1,0);
O= (0,0);
label("$x$",(1.2,0),SE);
label("$y$",(0,1.2),NE);

P = rotate(210)*A;
D = foot(P,A,-A);
draw(O--P--D);
draw(rightanglemark(O,D,P,2));
draw(Circle(O,1));
label("$O$",O,SE);
label("$P$",P,SW);
//label("$A$",A,SE);
label("$D$",D,N);
[/asy]

Triangle $POD$ is a 30-60-90 triangle, so $DO = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$ and $DP = \frac12$.  Therefore, the coordinates of $P$ are $\left(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}, -\frac12\right)$, so $$\tan 210^\circ =\frac{\sin 210^\circ}{\cos 210^\circ} = \frac{-1/2}{-\sqrt{3}/2} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = \boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}.$$

